SIMPLE: starboard
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Starboard
<hw>Star"board`</hw> <pr>(-b⟦omac⟧rd` ⟦or⟧ -b⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sterbord</ets>, AS.
<ets>ste⟦oacute⟧rbord</ets>, i.e., steer board. See <er>Steer</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Board</er> of a vessel, and cf.
<er>Larboard</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>That side of a vessel
which is on the right hand of a person who stands on board facing the
bow; -- opposed to <ant>larboard</ant>, or <ant>port</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Starboard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Starboard
<hw>Star"board`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Pertaining
to the right-hand side of a ship; being or lying on the right side;
<as>as, the <ex>starboard</ex> shrouds; <ex>starboard</ex> quarter;
<ex>starboard</ex> tack.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Starboard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Starboard
<hw>Star"board`</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To put to
the right, or starboard, side of a vessel; <as>as, to <ex>starboard</ex>
the helm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Star-bowlines</ent>⟦br⟧
